author: Jeff Seidel
title: Late arrival can't stop city champ Ijeoma Ike-Amaechi
text:
(Jeff Seidel) 
"They were just awesome today," Downer said. "I thought our top five was strong. I definitely thought we had a chance [to win]." 
Digital Harbor had an easier time winning its team title. Dash led the way as the Rams placed five runners in the top 15 overall and finished with 43 points to easily top runner-up Poly (74). 
Coach Lutalo Bakari said his team has been pointing toward running well in the city, region and state meets — the season's biggest races — throughout the fall. 
"We know that this is the first of three hills," Bakari said. "Now we'll prepare for the next one." 
Dash trailed Edmondson's Frankye Duckett for much of the race before taking off with about 400 yards left. The junior finished in 17:35.17 to edge Duckett (17:40.07). 
Duckett led for much of this race but that didn't bother Dash. The junior simply wanted to stay within about 10 meters of Duckett so he'd be ready to make a late move. He did just that throughout the run, and everything then played out perfectly at the end. 
"I knew exactly where to kick," Dash said. "I was just trying to run smart. I was second the whole race. I tried to stay with him the whole time." 
Teammate Lyndon Burrell finished third. Marquise Hill (11th), Berkeley Todd (13th) and Criss Dzaringa (15th) rounded out the Digital Harbor top five as the Rams showed their depth.
